04818nam a22007095i 9781478009153DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019041100  a97814780091537 a10.1515/97814780091532doi  a(DE-B1597)553010  a(OCoLC)1120689050  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aHQ72.U53bH355 2020 7aSOC0320002bisacsh04a306.772231 aHarkins, Gillian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aVirtual Pedophilia :bSex Offender Profiling and U.S. Security Culture /cGillian Harkins. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (286 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION: VIRTUAL PEDOPHILIA -- tONE. MONSTROUS SEXUALITY AND VILE SOVEREIGNTY -- tTWO. PROFILING VIRTUALITY AND PEDOPHILIC DATA -- tTHREE. INFORMATIONAL IMAGE AND PROCEDURAL TONE -- tFOUR. CAPTURING THE PAST AND THE VITALITY OF CRIME -- tFIVE. CAPTURING THE FUTURE AND THE SEXUALITY OF RISK -- tCONCLUSION. EXCEPTIONAL PEDOPHILIA AND THE EVERYDAY CASE -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Virtual Pedophilia Gillian Harkins traces how by the end of the twentieth century the pedophile as a social outcast evolved into its contemporary appearance as a virtually normal white male. The pedophile's alleged racial and gender normativity was treated as an exception to dominant racialized modes of criminal or diagnostic profiling. The pedophile was instead profiled as a virtual figure, a potential threat made visible only when information was transformed into predictive image. The virtual pedophile was everywhere and nowhere, slipping through day-to-day life undetected until people learned how to arm themselves with the right combination of visually predictive information. Drawing on television, movies, and documentaries such as Law and Order: SVU, To Catch a Predator, Mystic River, and Capturing the Friedmans, Harkins shows how diverse U.S. audiences have been conscripted and trained to be lay detectives who should always be on the lookout for the pedophile as virtual predator. In this way, the perceived threat of the pedophile legitimated increased surveillance and ramped-up legal strictures that expanded the security apparatus of the carceral state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aComputer crimesxInvestigationzUnited States. 0aInternet and childrenxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aMass media and crimezUnited States. 0aOnline sexual predatorszUnited States. 0aPedophilia in mass mediaxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aPedophiliaxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aSex offenderszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069631808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478009153zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478009153423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478009153.jpg  a978-3-11-069631-8  DUP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070474-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Eng